{"pageProps":{"tutorial":{"title":"HTML Data Attributes","slug":"html-data-attributes","subject":"HTML","category":"Web Development","level":"Intermediate","estimated_read_time":"10 minutes","prerequisites":["HTML Attributes"],"learning_objectives":["Understand custom data-* attributes","Store extra information in HTML tags","Access data attributes using JavaScript (dataset)","Style elements using attribute selectors"],"theory":"# HTML Data Attributes\n\nSometimes you need to store extra data associated with an element, but there is no standard HTML attribute for it. HTML5 allows us to create our own attributes using the `data-*` prefix.\n\n## Syntax\n\n`data-name=\"value\"`\n\n*   The attribute name must start with `data-`.\n*   It should contain lowercase letters only.\n\n## Example\n\n```html\n<div id=\"product1\" data-price=\"49.99\" data-category=\"shoes\" data-stock=\"10\">\n  Nike Air Max\n</div>\n```\n\n## Accessing Data in JavaScript\n\nYou can read these values easily using the `dataset` property.\n\n```javascript\nconst product = document.getElementById('product1');\nlet price = product.dataset.price; // \"49.99\"\nlet category = product.dataset.category; // \"shoes\"\n```\n\n## Accessing in CSS\n\nYou can use the `attr()` function or attribute selectors.\n\n```css\ndiv[data-stock=\"0\"] {\n  color: red;\n  content: \"Out of Stock\";\n}\n```","syntax":"<element data-key=\"value\">","examples":[{"code":"<ul>\n  <li data-animal-type=\"bird\">Owl</li>\n  <li data-animal-type=\"fish\">Salmon</li>\n</ul>\n<script>\n  // JS: element.dataset.animalType (CamelCase)\n</script>","output":"Hidden data attached to list items.","explanation":"Note that data-animal-type becomes dataset.animalType in JS."}],"common_mistakes":[{"mistake":"Using data attributes for sensitive info","correction":"Never store passwords or private keys in data attributes. They are visible in 'View Source'.","example":"Public data only."},{"mistake":"Uppercase naming","correction":"HTML attributes are case-insensitive, but dataset property converts them to camelCase. Stick to lowercase-dash naming.","example":"Use data-user-id, not data-UserID."}],"interview_questions":[{"question":"How do you access a data attribute named 'data-user-id' in JavaScript?","difficulty":"Easy","answer":"Using the dataset property: element.dataset.userId (Note the camelCase conversion)."},{"question":"What are data attributes used for?","difficulty":"Intermediate","answer":"They are used to store custom data private to the page or application (like ID, state, config) directly in the HTML structure."}],"practice_problems":[{"difficulty":"Beginner","problem":"Add a data attribute to a button storing the user ID '12345'.","hint":"Use data-user-id.","solution":"<button data-user-id=\"12345\">Profile</button>"}],"real_world_use_cases":[{"scenario":"JavaScript Frameworks","description":"Libraries often use data attributes to configure plugins (e.g., Bootstrap tooltips uses data-toggle=\"tooltip\").","code":"<button data-toggle=\"modal\">"}],"exam_notes":["Must start with data-","Accessed via element.dataset.key","Hyphens convert to camelCase in JS","Good for storing state within DOM"],"summary":"Data attributes allow you to extend HTML with your own custom attributes. They are perfect for bridging the gap between your HTML structure and JavaScript logic, letting you embed configuration data directly into your elements.","order":10},"courseTutorials":[{"slug":"html-document-structure","path":"content/html/html-document-structure.json","title":"HTML Document Structure","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":2},{"slug":"html-comments","path":"content/html/html-comments.json","title":"HTML Comments","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":3},{"slug":"html-editors","path":"content/html/html-editors.json","title":"HTML Editors & Tools","category":"Web Development","subject":"HTML","description":"","order":4},{"slug":"html-ele